Nocturne no. Eighteen

I am annoyed of the clinging in this abandoned room, and I've
grown tired of laying in this bed. I am sick from loneliness
and thought. This is a quiet illness. The only company to
be found a watch, and all it will tell me is the time, and then
only if asked. We lived, together, in silence so viscous that it
became difficult to hear each other. Torn souls, draped in
moist arpeggios and rain; smoke and silt. Memories (or perhaps, forgetfulnesses)
started to fail us and the darkness over our eyes rose, steadily like
the cumbersome and petulant tides. Once again, I bumble out
down the hall to answer the wind, knowing she's not there. The
closeness that was never truth is gone. She did love something in
me, it seems. I became convinced once, for a moment, when peering around
her soul through her eyes. But here, removed, I find myself lost for the
gutter like lost mutton or a single soiled and discarded sock . . . and the
long-muted colors that once danced within her smile are now my own.
